an important southern Senator in the U.S. Congress from 1933 to 1936 during the first phase of
the New Deal, playing an important role in the creation of the Tennessee Valley Authority and
the passage of the Social Security Act; and
WHEREAS, Pearl Duke Bachman, Senator Bachman's wife, had significant involvement
in the local Garden Club movement and was an early advocate for land conservation and other
social causes; and
WHEREAS, their daughter, Martha Bachman McCoy, became a powerful voice for
highway beautification and reverence for history, good citizenship, and mountain unity; and
WHEREAS, Martha Bachman McCoy and her family became the farm's primary
residents circa 1940; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. McCoy and her daughter, Sally McCoy Garland, allowed the Town of
Walden to acquire the farm through a gift/sale, so that the land might serve the community as
an arboretum, natural area, and venue for public and private events; and
WHEREAS, today, the property, known as McCoy Farm and Gardens, covers thirty-eight
acres and contains the historic home, barn, and outbuildings of the Bachman farming era, as
well as many gardens, a Level 2 arboretum, and 2.4 miles of trails; and
WHEREAS, McCoy Farm and Gardens is open daily, hosts various community events,
offers a venue for private events, and is enjoyed by the broader community for its natural beauty
and historic charm; and
WHEREAS, this General Assembly finds it appropriate to honor the Bachman-McCoy
family for their many contributions to social causes, environmental preservation, and good
citizenship and their generosity in giving their farm to the Walden community, so that present
and future generations may learn history and enjoy nature while visiting the property; now,
therefore,
